The Data does not contain any NULL Values¶
The 6 variables that denote the biomechanics attributes are all numeric and are float variables¶
The Class variable is string type as expected. However, we need to further check the Class variable to see if the data has 3 classes as expected or has some unexpected classes or missing data that is denoted by some unexpected class¶
In [6]:
## Figuring out if there are other categories in the class variable have values other than the three identified classes

df.Class.unique()
Out[6]:

Although the 'Class' variable does not have any missing values denoted by signs such as '?' or '--' etc. It does have typos that need to be corrected¶
In [7]:
## Replacing the wrong labels in the class variables

df = df.replace(to_replace='Nrmal', value='Normal')
df = df.replace(to_replace='type_h', value='Type_H')
df = df.replace(to_replace='tp_s', value='Type_S')

df.Class.unique()
Out[7]:
array(['Normal', 'Type_H', 'Type_S'], dtype=object)

## ANOVA to check if Class is dependent on P_incidence

import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols

mod = ols('P_incidence ~ Class', data = df).fit()
aov_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(mod, typ = 2)
print(aov_table)

                sum_sq     df          F        PR(>F)
Class     35892.191585    2.0  98.539709  8.752849e-34
Residual  55910.976950  307.0        NaN           NaN

since p value <0.05 we reject the Null Hypothesis that the average P_incidence for all classes is same. Therefore Class is dependent on P_incidence

The Ratio of the classes in the train set vs the test is more or less similar¶

We see that in the train set class Normal has 31% of the data points, class Type_H has 19% of the data points, class Type_S has 50% of the data points

Although the classes are slightly imbalanced if we try to undersample to achieve target balancing we will lose out data.

If we try to copy and add more data for the 'Normal' and 'Type_H' classes we will not really be adding any data.

Thirdly, we can use techniques like SMOTE to get synthetic data for the two classes (Normal and Type_H), but we would be adding bias.

Since the classes are only slightly imbalanced. In my opinion we do not need to perform any undersampling or oversampling.¶

    accuracy                           0.83        93
   macro avg       0.80      0.78      0.79        93
weighted avg       0.83      0.83      0.82        93

The Classification report states the Precision, Recall and F1-Score of the three classes and it gives a better measure of model performance than just accuracy

Recall gives us the correct predictions of the given class out of all the times the class occurs in the dataset The recall for Normal is 0.84, Type_H is 0.58 and Type_S is 0.93 Therefore we can say that if the class Normal occurs 100 times in the data we predicted it correctly 84 times

Precision gives us what proportion of positive classification for every class was actually correct The precision for Normal is 0.75, Type_H is 0.73 and Type_S is 0.93 Therefore we can say if we classified a 100 patients in the Normal category we were right 75 times

F1 Score is a combination of both the metrics Precision and Recall. It balances the aspects of both Precision and Recall. It is the harmonic mean of Precision and Recall

The F1 Score for Normal is 0.79, Type_H is 0.65 and Type_S is 0.93

Therefore we see that we are able to predict Type_S well while prediction for Type_H and Normal Categories is rather poor

Choosing the best tuned model with K, distance_measures, weights and parameter p¶

In [95]:
## Creating a dataframe with the Hyperparameters and the accuracies achieved with the Hyperparameters

model_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['K','p','Weights','Metric','Accuracy'])
iter = 0
for i in range(1,75,2):
    for j in range(1,3):
        for l in ['uniform', 'distance']:
            for m in ['minkowski','chebyshev']:                    
                model_KNN_3 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=i, metric= m, p = j, weights = l)
                model_KNN_3.fit(X_train,y_train)
                score = round(model_KNN_3.score(X_test,y_test),3)
                model_df = model_df.append(pd.DataFrame({'K':i,'p':j,'Weights':l,'Metric':m, 'Accuracy':score}, index = [iter]))
                iter = iter+1

Conclusion and Improvisation¶

Conclusion on the results¶

The model prediction results show that it is not very easy to distinguish between the three different classes with the current data set. Although Type_H and Type_S are distinguishable more easily. It is difficult to distinguish the fringe cases of the class Normal from the two classes.

We see that the prediction errors have happened only in trying to distinuguish class Normal from Type_H and Normal from Type_S

We also see that the variable S_degree helps identify Type_S quite well.

Recall gives us the correct predictions of the given class out of all the times the class occurs in the dataset The recall for Normal is 0.88, Type_H is 0.79 and Type_S is 0.93 Therefore we can say that if the class Normal occurs 100 times in the data we predicted it correctly 88 times

Precision gives us what proportion of positive classification for every class was actually correct The precision for Normal is 0.80, Type_H is 0.88 and Type_S is 0.95 Therefore we can say if we classified 100 patients in the Type_H category we were right 88 times

F1 Score is a combination of both the metrics Precision and Recall. It balances the aspects of both Precision and Recall. It is the harmonic mean of Precision and Recall

The F1 Score for Normal is 0.84, Type_H is 0.83 and Type_S is 0.94

This result from the final model is way better than the result on the first model.

Detailed suggestions or improvements or on quality, quantity, variety, velocity, veracity etc. on the data points collected by the research team to perform a better data analysis in future.¶

  1. While collecting data it would be better if we categorized data well. For example we had categories such as Nrml and tp_s etc also in the data that make data cleansing a necessary step and can also create a situation where the data analyst/scientist can make some wrong analysis
  1. While collecting data it would be better if we can collect data equally for all classes otherwise we may have a situation of imbalanced classes
  1. If the data is related to medical conditions, we must strive to find variables that better define the conditions. If the predictability of the variables is not very high, we may end up with models with low accuracy and therefore may misclassify conditions
  1. There are no questions or suggestions on variety, velocity and veracity as data is tabular, static and seems to have come from a research team
